How can I implement a neural network with multiple hidden layers to solve a classification problem using JavaScript? Also, what is the function of hidden layers in a neural network and how do they affect the model's accuracy? And why is it important to incorporate regularization methods while training a neural network with multiple hidden layers? Lastly, can you explain how altering the number of layers and neurons in the neural network can lead to overfitting if the network becomes too complex? 
As for the specific JavaScript code, here's an example of how to create a neural network with multiple hidden layers using the brain.js library:
const brain = require('brain.js');
const net = new brain.NeuralNetwork({
  hiddenLayers: [4, 5, 6] // specify the number of neurons in each hidden layer
});
net.train([{input: [0, 0], output: [0]},
           {input: [0, 1], output: [1]},
           {input: [1, 0], output: [1]},
           {input: [1, 1], output: [0]}]); // train the neural network with sample data
And to prevent overfitting, you can incorporate regularization methods such as L1 and L2 regularization.

given typescript file
import { pipe } from "fp-ts/function";
import \* as RA from "fp-ts/ReadonlyArray";
import \* as S from "fp-ts/string";

import type { WatchDataAnalytics } from "#pkg/app/types/watch\_data\_analytics";
import { getPrismaClient } from "#pkg/libs/prisma";

import { buildTimestampFilter } from "./\_build\_timestamp\_filter";
import { calcMinMaxAverage } from "./\_calc\_min\_max\_average";
import { formatGroupItemCount } from "./\_format\_group\_item\_count";
import { msToS } from "./\_ms\_to\_s";

type Options = {
 readonly videoId: string;
 readonly gid: string;
 readonly since?: number | undefined;
 readonly until?: number | undefined;
};

/\*\* @package \*/
export const analyzeWatchData = async ({ videoId, gid, since, until }: Options): Promise => {
 const db = getPrismaClient();

 const timestamp = buildTimestampFilter({ since, until });

 const chapterMenuClickEventLogs = await db.v2ChapterMenuClickEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["chapterId"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const chapterMenuClickCount = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: chapterMenuClickEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "chapterId",
 });

 const chapterRecommendationButtonClickEventLogs = await db.v2ChapterRecommendationButtonClickEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["chapterId"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const chapterRecommendationButtonClickCount = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: chapterRecommendationButtonClickEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "chapterId",
 });

 const contactFormSubmitCount = await db.v2ContactFormSubmitEventLog.count({
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });

 const dockMenuClickEventLogs = await db.v2DockMenuClickEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["target"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const dockMenuClickCount = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: dockMenuClickEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "target",
 });

 const documentPageViewEventLogs = await db.v2DocumentPageViewEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["page"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const documentPageView = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: documentPageViewEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "page",
 });

 const leaveCount = await db.v2LeaveEventLog.count({
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });

 const meetingReservationButtonClickEventLogs = await db.v2MeetingReservationButtonClickEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["staffId"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const meetingReservationButtonClickCount = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: meetingReservationButtonClickEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "staffId",
 });

 const meetingStaffInfoButtonClickEventLogs = await db.v2MeetingStaffInfoButtonClickEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["staffId"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const meetingStaffInfoButtonClickCount = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: meetingStaffInfoButtonClickEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "staffId",
 });

 const messageSendCount = await db.v2MessageSendEventLog.count({
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });

 const modeEnterEventLogs = await db.v2ModeEnterEventLog.groupBy({
 by: ["mode"],
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 \_count: { \_all: true }, // eslint-disable-line @typescript-eslint/naming-convention
 });
 const modeEnterCount = formatGroupItemCount({
 groups: modeEnterEventLogs,
 groupedBy: "mode",
 });

 const pageViewCount = await db.v2PageViewEventLog.count({
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });

 const messageSendEventLogs = await db.v2MessageSendEventLog.findMany({
 select: { body: true, replyingTo: true },
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });
 const talkAnswersCount: WatchDataAnalytics["talkAnswersCount"] = {};
 for (const messageSendEventLog of messageSendEventLogs) {
 if (messageSendEventLog.replyingTo == null) continue;
 const countMap = (talkAnswersCount[messageSendEventLog.replyingTo] ??= {}); // eslint-disable-line functional/immutable-data
 const count = (countMap[messageSendEventLog.body] ??= 0); // eslint-disable-line functional/immutable-data
 countMap[messageSendEventLog.body] = count + 1; // eslint-disable-line functional/immutable-data
 }

 const uniqueUsers = await db.v2PageViewEventLog.findMany({
 select: { id: true },
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 distinct: ["uid"],
 });
 const uniqueUserCount = uniqueUsers.length;

 const videoEndCount = await db.v2VideoEndEventLog.count({
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });

 const videoStartCount = await db.v2VideoStartEventLog.count({
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });

 const videoPlayWhileEventLogs = await db.v2VideoPlayWhileEventLog.findMany({
 select: { sessionId: true, duration: true },
 where: {
 videoId,
 gid,
 timestamp,
 },
 });
 const watchDurations = pipe(
 videoPlayWhileEventLogs,
 RA.map(({ sessionId }) => sessionId),
 RA.uniq(S.Eq),
 RA.map((sessionId) =>
 pipe(
 videoPlayWhileEventLogs,
 RA.filter((e) => e.sessionId === sessionId),
 RA.map(({ duration }) => duration),
 RA.reduce(0, (a, b) => a + b),
 msToS
 )
 )
 );

 return {
 chapterMenuClickCount,
 chapterRecommendationButtonClickCount,
 contactFormSubmitCount,
 dockMenuClickCount,
 documentPageView,
 leaveCount,
 meetingReservationButtonClickCount,
 meetingStaffInfoButtonClickCount,
 messageSendCount,
 modeEnterCount,
 pageViewCount,
 talkAnswersCount,
 uniqueUserCount,
 videoEndCount,
 videoStartCount,
 watchDuration: calcMinMaxAverage(watchDurations),
 };
};

What Java code can be used to display the list of books from various genres and authors on an HTML page to enhance our reading experience?
Here's a sample Java code that uses HTML to display a list of books with their corresponding authors and genres:
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
public class Book {
    private String title;
    private String author;
    private String genre;

    public Book(String title, String author, String genre) {
        this.title = title;
        this.author = author;
        this.genre = genre;
    }

    public String getTitle() {
        return title;
    }

    public String getAuthor() {
        return author;
    }

    public String getGenre() {
        return genre;
    }
}
public class BookList {
    private List<Book> books = new ArrayList<Book>();

    public void addBook(Book book) {
        books.add(book);
    }

    public List<Book> getBooks() {
        return books;
    }
}
public class BookHTMLPage {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BookList bookList = new BookList();
        bookList.addBook(new Book("The Great Gatsby", "F. Scott Fitzgerald", "Classic"));
        bookList.addBook(new Book("Beloved", "Toni Morrison", "Historical Fiction"));
        bookList.addBook(new Book("The Hunger Games", "Suzanne Collins", "Science Fiction"));
        bookList.addBook(new Book("The Catcher in the Rye", "J.D. Salinger", "Young Adult"));

        System.out.println("<html>");
        System.out.println("<head>");
        System.out.println("<title>Book List</title>");
        System.out.println("</head>");
        System.out.println("<body>");
        System.out.println("<h1>Recommended Book List</h1>");
        System.out.println("<table>");
        System.out.println("<tr><th>Title</th><th>Author</th><th>Genre</th></tr>");
        for(Book book : bookList.getBooks()) {
            System.out.println("<tr><td>" + book.getTitle() + "</td><td>" + book.getAuthor() + "</td><td>" + book.getGenre() + "</td></tr>");
        }
        System.out.println("</table>");
        System.out.println("</body>");
        System.out.println("</html>");
    }
}
With this Java code, we can create a list of recommended books with their corresponding authors and genres, and display them on an HTML page for easy browsing and selection. This can enhance our reading experience by introducing us to new and diverse literary adventures outside of our usual genre preferences.

