Imagine you are building a virtual assistant for a customer service team. You want to create a program that can analyze customer complaints and generate a response based on the severity of the issue. 
Here's an example of a Go code snippet that uses natural language processing to classify the severity of a customer complaint:
```
package main
import (
	"fmt"
	"github.com/jbrukh/bayesian"
)
func main() {
	// create a new classifier
	classifier := bayesian.NewClassifier(bayesian.Config{
		NonZeroClassPrior: 0.5,
	})
	// train the classifier with example data
	// first parameter is the document, second is the class
	classifier.Learn([]string{"The product arrived damaged"}, "high")
	classifier.Learn([]string{"The product is not working as expected"}, "medium")
	classifier.Learn([]string{"I have a question about my order"}, "low")
	// classify a new document
	scores, likely, _ := classifier.LogScores([]string{"The product is missing a component"})
	fmt.Println(scores, likely)
}
```
In this example, we use the Bayesian package to train the classifier with example customer complaints and their corresponding severity levels (high, medium, and low). The program then analyzes a new customer complaint and predicts its severity level based on the trained classifier. 
This kind of program could be very useful for customer service teams, as it would allow them to quickly categorize and prioritize customer complaints based on their severity level.

